and bioethics, Bennett grapples with contemporary efforts to mobilize human dignity as a counter-response to the biopolitics of the human body, and the breakdowns this has generated. To do this, he investigates how actors in pivotal institutions —the Vatican, the United Nations, U.S. Federal Bioethics—reconceived human dignity as the bearer of intrinsic worth, only to become frustrated by the Sisyphean struggle of turning its conceptions into practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBioethics. 0aHuman rights. 0aRespect for persons. 4aAnthropology. 4aBioethics. 4aTheology. 70(DE-588)4006791-90(DE-627)1045852340(DE-576)208867074aBioethik2gnd 70(DE-588)4038654-50(DE-627)1062312190(DE-576)209031360aMenschenwürde2gnd 7aMEDICAL / Ethics.2bisacsh  aBioethics.  aCommission on Human Rights.  aHuman Dignity.  aPresident's Council on Bioethics.  aVatican II.  aanthropology.  abiopower.  ahuman rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823267798zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823267798423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823267798/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK